In this article, President Barack Obama issues a proclamation for Labor Day, celebrating the contributions and resilience of America's workers. He acknowledges the achievements of the labor movement, such as weekends, 40-hour workweeks, minimum wage, and collective bargaining rights. President Obama also highlights the progress made during his administration, including job growth, wage increases, and efforts to protect and support the middle class. He emphasizes the importance of fair treatment and compensation for workers, occupational health and safety, paid leave, apprenticeships, retirement security, closing the gender pay gap, and promoting diversity in the workforce. The President concludes by urging unity and commitment to creating positive change for workers and future generations.